Modifying CSS

Tying CSS Changes to User Interaction

The Element.style property #

The easiest way to change CSS styles on an HTML element using Javascript is to access individual styles in the Element.style property.

Since Element.style is also an object, there are many sub-properties that target specific CSS properties. For instance, we could add a border to an element using Element.style.border:

  • HTML
  • JavaScript
1
2
3
4
5
6
7
8
<html>
 <head>
   <title>Modifying CSS with Element.style</title>
 </head>
 <body>
   <h1>This element should have a border.</h1>
 </body>
</html>
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview
1
2
var h1 = document.querySelector('h1');
h1.style.border = "3px dashed black";
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview

We could also change the text alignment with Element.style.textAlign:

  • HTML
  • JavaScript

3
4

7
8
<html>
 <head>
   <title>Modifying CSS with Element.style</title>
 </head>
 <body>
   <h1>This element should be centered and have a border.</h1>
 </body>
</html>
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview
1
2
3
var h1 = document.querySelector('h1');
h1.style.border = "3px dashed black";
h1.style.textAlign = "center";
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview

There are many, many CSS properties that can be accessed within Element.style. A full list can be found here. Browse through the list to get a sense of the different properties you can target using Javascript.

Programmatically styling with classes using Element.classList #

Although it is perfectly valid to modify styles with Element.style, what if you want to modify multiple CSS properties?

For instance, let’s say we want to highlight an element when we click it by changing both the background-color and color. Using Element.style, the code would look something like this:

  • HTML
  • JavaScript
1
2
3
4
5
6
7
8
<html>
 <head>
   <title>Applying Multiple Styles</title>
 </head>
 <body>
   <h1>Highlight this element on a click</h1>
 </body>
</html>
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview
1
2
3
4
5
6
var h1 = document.querySelector('h1');
h1.onclick = function(){
  this.style.color = 'white';
  this.style.backgroundColor = 'blue';
}
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview

However, a better way to add multiple styles would be to create a class with those CSS properties and then add the class to the HTML element. We can use Element.classList to:

  • check the class values associated with an element
  • add/remove classes toggle class values
  • check whether a certain class is associated with an element
  • replace one class with another class

Let’s go back to the previous example. We could highlight the h1 element using Element.classList.add(class):

  • HTML
  • CSS
  • JavaScript
1
2
3
4
5
6
7
8
<html>
 <head>
   <title>Applying Multiple Styles</title>
 </head>
 <body>
   <h1>Highlight this element on a click</h1>
 </body>
</html>
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview
1
2
3
4
.highlight {
  color: white;
  background-color: blue;
}
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview
1
2
3
4
5
var h1 = document.querySelector('h1');
h1.onclick = function(){
  this.classList.add('highlight');
}
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview

We could also toggle the “highlight” behavior using Element.classList.toggle(class):

  • HTML
  • CSS
  • JavaScript
1
2
3
4
5
6
7
8
<html>
 <head>
   <title>Applying Multiple Styles</title>
 </head>
 <body>

 </body>
</html>
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview
1
2
3
4
.highlight {
  color: white;
  background-color: blue;
}
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview
1
2
3
4
5
var h1 = document.querySelector('h1');
h1.onclick = function(){
  this.classList.toggle('highlight');
}
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview

Additionally, you can use Element.classList.remove(class) to remove a class and Element.classList.contains(class) to check if the element has a certain class value associated with it. To replace one class with another, use Element.classList.replace(oldClass, newClass).
